KPI Performance Summary
Overall supply chain performance in Q1 2026 is stable but below target on service and availability in key growth categories.

OTIF: 91% and Service level: 92% – Acceptable but below best-in-class FMCG benchmarks (95%+), indicating service risk.
Forecast accuracy: 78% – Moderate; misalignment evident in both fast-growing premium lines and declining budget segments.
Stockout rate: 8% – Elevated, especially in premium skincare (North/East) and budget skincare (low-sales cluster).
Inventory turns: 5.4 – Moderate; constrained by slow-moving budget makeup and budget skincare in several regions.
Excess inventory: $120,000 – Primarily in budget makeup and budget skincare with falling demand trends.
Premium skincare fill rate (North & East): 84% – Critical gap in a high-growth category.
Budget skincare availability (low-sales cluster): 68% – Significant service issue in smaller regions.
In summary, the business is under-serving high-growth premium segments while holding excess stock in declining budget categories.

Key Risks
Stockouts in High-Growth Premium Skincare

East: 4 days cover with 300 units delayed by 7 days.
North: 5 days cover and no incoming stock.
Rising or sharply rising demand in both regions.
Direct impact on revenue and brand equity.
Supply Delays Impacting Service KPIs

Replenishment issues for premium skincare are driving lower fill rates (84%) and reducing OTIF.
Excess Inventory in Declining Budget Segments

Budget makeup shows 25–34 days cover in most regions despite falling demand.
Budget skincare has 20–26+ days cover in multiple regions with declining or stable demand.
Risk of obsolescence, markdowns, and working capital lock-up.
Low Availability in Low-Sales Cluster

Budget skincare availability at 68% with frequent stockouts despite low overall demand.
Indicates poor replenishment logic rather than demand volume issue.
Planning and Data Fragmentation

Separate spreadsheets across sales and inventory teams are slowing reaction time and contributing to forecast inaccuracy (78%) and misaligned stock deployment.
